# Rule: CQRS project structure

Apply this to **solution layout and dependencies**. Replace `{Solution}` with your assembly prefix (multiple solutions can share the same rule text).

## Logical layers ↔ typical .NET projects

| Layer | Role | Example projects (`src/` …) |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Core** | Domain, use-case handlers, boundary contracts | `{Solution}.Domain`, `{Solution}.Application`, `{Solution}.Contracts` |
| **Infra** | Persistence, external integrations | `{Solution}.Infrastructure` |
| **EndPoint** | HTTP/host, composition root | `{Solution}.Api` (or `Web`, `Gateway`, …)

### Responsibility split

- **Domain**: entities/value objects/domain services; depends only on primitives/BCL (+ optional narrowly scoped libraries). Generally **does not** reference Application, Contracts, Infra, or Api.
- **Application**: CQRS handlers, pipelines, app abstractions (**e.g.** `IDbContext`/`IRepository`/`IUnitOfWork` **defined here or in Domain**, implemented in Infra). **Handlers** reference boundary **Commands/Queries** by type; handlers do **not** hide parallel copies of those messages unless you deliberately split tiers.
- **Contracts** (or equivalent): outward-facing payloads + MediatR `*Command`/`*Query` if your team follows “one shared message type”; response `*Dto`/`*Response`. Often references **MediatR** NuGet only, not other inner projects — unless you adopt shared kernel from Domain intentionally.
- **Infra**: implements persistence/integration; references Application abstractions **and Domain** where needed; not Api.
- **Api**: controllers/minimal APIs, auth wiring as needed, validators; delegates work via MediatR; **no** direct persistence.

## Vertical slices in **Contracts** (recommended layout)

Boundary types grouped by **feature + use case**, not giant `Requests`/`Responses` folders.

```
{Area}/
  Commands/
    {UseCase}/                 # Submit, Cancel, UpdateStatus …
      … *.cs boundary types / messages + optional slice DTOs

  Queries/
    {UseCase}/                 # GetById, Search …
      … *.cs queries + read models for that slice

Common/                         # shared error envelope, paging, …
```

**Namespaces** mirror folders, e.g. `{Solution}.Contracts.{Area}.Commands.{UseCase}`.

## Single source for messages (optional convention)

Many teams define **Commands/Queries in Contracts** (with `MediatR` on that project). Endpoint binds or constructs them and calls `Send`; handlers implement `IRequestHandler<TRequest, …>` for the **same** `TRequest`.

| Where | Naming | Role |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Contracts** | `*Command`, `*Query` | `IRequest` / `IRequest<T>`; wire + mediator message (if combined). |
| **Contracts** | `*Dto`, `*Response` | Response/read payloads for slices. |
| **Application** | `*CommandHandler`, `*QueryHandler` | Only handlers in the mirrored slice folders — **not** a second `{Same}Command.cs` next to them. |

**Route + body:** merge path/query into the canonical message once in Endpoint before `Send` (same idea as described in `.cursor/rules/mediatr-controllers.mdc`).

**Alternative:** keep transport DTOs (`*Request`) separate from mediator messages — consistent with `.cursor/rules/reuse-portable-rules.mdc` (**pattern**, not mandated product choice).

### Infra (Command vs read stores)

Separate **writes** and **reads** conceptually (`CommandDb` / `QueryDb`). A **single** `DbContext` is acceptable **if** handlers stay pure write vs pure read — split later if coupling hurts.

### Endpoint

Hosting, Swagger/OpenAPI, auth, validation registrations, middleware-only composition; delegates to handlers via MediatR.

## CQRS rules

- Commands mutate; queries do **not**.
- Prefer one handler per Command/Query; don’t fuse unrelated write/read in one class.

## Dependency direction (inward)

- Domain ← **no** Infrastructure/Api.
- Application ← Domain + Contracts (typical); **no** Api; **no** Infrastructure project reference if you keep ports in Application/Domain.
- Infrastructure ← Application abstractions + Domain as needed; **no** Api.
- Contracts ← BCL + **optional** MediatR; **no** inner projects unless you document an exception.
- Api ← Contracts + Application + Infrastructure (composition only).

## Naming & folder mirroring

- Contracts: `{Area}/{Commands|Queries}/{UseCase}/` — one capability per folder.
- Application: mirror path for **handlers only**, e.g. `{Feature}/Commands/{UseCase}/SubmitEnvelopeCommandHandler.cs` — no duplicate `SubmitEnvelopeCommand.cs` in Application **when** Contracts owns the message.
